^b@2mitche: Ok - ready for "serious 3NT"?

So - in tonite's hands, there were several deals where you got into a Game-Forcing (GF) auction and had to decide 
whether to stop short or try for slam
How do you know whether to do this?
let's consider  this auction| 

fp|1|cp|2|cs|1|ht|m|at|
^b{ 1@h - 2@d/ 2@h - 3@h }|fp|1|ht|n|cs|3|at|


First, we recognize that this is a GF.  And that 2@h could be a 5 card suit
So 3@h is a good 3-card raise --- right? 
With 4 card heart support, responder would have used Jacoby 2NT

Now - opener can 
a) sign off in 4@H 
b) cue bid
Since responder's hand is completely unlimited, opener may feel compelled to cue bid.
Are we all agreeed so far?

How does opener say "I have a better than minimum hand, but just in case you have a minimum, 
I would like you to stop in game"|
